  "text": "Django implements lazy querysets through a two-stage process: lazy SQL compilation and lazy query execution. When a queryset is first iterated, an OperationalError can be raised if the database is unavailable.\n\nLazy Compilation and Storage:\nThe QuerySet class in django/db/models/query.py stores a Query object representing the ORM query without compiling or executing SQL. The QuerySet.__init__ method (line 317) sets self._iterable_class = ModelIterable, which is the default iterable class that will execute the query when needed.\n\nLazy Evaluation Trigger:\nWhen a queryset is first iterated (e.g., via for loop, list(), or str()), the __iter__() method in django/db/models/query.py (lines 396-412) is invoked. This method calls self._fetch_all() to populate the results cache, which is the first point where database access occurs.\n\nQuerySet Result Fetching:\nThe _fetch_all() method in django/db/models/query.py (lines 2168-2172) instantiates the iterable class (ModelIterable by default) and converts it to a list, which triggers the iteration and executes the query.\n\nDatabase Query Execution:\nThe ModelIterable.__iter__() method in django/db/models/query.py (lines 88-150+) is where the actual SQL is executed. It obtains a SQLCompiler instance from the Query object, then calls compiler.execute_sql() which is implemented in django/db/models/sql/compiler.py.\n\nSQL Query Compilation:\nThe SQLCompiler.as_sql() method in django/db/models/sql/compiler.py (lines 763-920+) performs lazy SQL compilation. This method is called when execute_sql() needs the SQL string and parameters. The as_sql() method constructs the complete SQL query from the ORM query object without executing it—the actual execution happens only when cursor.execute() is called.\n\nDatabase Cursor Execution:\nThe SQLCompiler.execute_sql() method in django/db/models/sql/compiler.py (lines 1601-1673) is where the compiled SQL is actually executed against the database. Line 1618 calls self.as_sql() to get the compiled SQL string and parameters, and line 1631 calls cursor.execute(sql, params), which raises an OperationalError if the database connection fails. The try-except block (lines 1630-1638) handles exceptions from cursor execution and attempts to close the cursor, re-raising the OperationalError if cursor.close() fails."
}

